Project setup and run guide (Windows)
------------------------------------
Prerequisites
- Python 3.11.x (64-bit recommended; use a fresh venv for this project).
- Node.js and npm (LTS recommended).
- Expo CLI tooling (bundled with `npx expo`) and Expo Go installed on your iPhone for testing.
- Git (optional, for version control).

Backend (FastAPI + YOLO) setup (GitBash)
1) From the `GuideFollowingApp` folder, create/activate a virtual environment:
   - Create: `py -3.11 -m venv .venv`
   - Activate: `source .venv/Scripts/activate`
2) Upgrade pip tooling:
   - `python -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel`
3) Install dependencies (force wheels to avoid compiling numpy/torch):
   - `python -m pip install --only-binary=:all: numpy==1.26.4`
   - CPU PyTorch wheels: `python -m pip install --only-binary=:all: torch torchvision torchaudio`
   - App deps: `python -m pip install fastapi uvicorn ultralytics pillow python-multipart`
   (If you prefer GPU and have CUDA, use the wheel index from pytorch.org.)
4) Run the backend (new terminal with the venv activated):
   - `uvicorn backend:app --reload --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000`
   - The API will be available at `http://<your-lan-ip>:8000/detect`.
Frontend (Expo) setup
1) Install JS deps (in `GuideFollowingApp`):
   - `npm install`
   - If not already installed: `npx expo install expo-camera @react-native-community/slider`
2) Run the Expo app (new terminal):
   - `npx expo start`
   - On iPhone, open Expo Go and scan the QR code. Make sure the phone and PC are on the same network.
3) Update the backend URL in `App.js` to use your PC’s LAN IP (e.g., `http://192.168.x.x:8000/detect`).
Running both together
- Terminal 1: activate venv and start backend: `uvicorn backend:app --reload --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000`
- Terminal 2: start Expo: `npx expo start`
- In the Expo app, take a photo; the app will POST it to `/detect` and display the person count from the backend response.
Common tips
- If you see numpy/torch trying to compile, verify you’re on Python 3.11 and using the `--only-binary=:all:` installs above.
- Keep the venv activated whenever running or installing backend Python packages.

Project setup and run guide (iOS Swift App)
------------------------------------
Prerequisites
- macOS with Xcode installed
- iPhone running iOS 15 or later
- Apple ID

iOS App (Xcode) first time setup
1) Clone the repository and open the project in Xcode
2) Connect your iphone to your Mac using a USB cable:
   - On your phone you will be asked if you "Trust This Computer" select yes
3) In Xcode make sure your iPhone appears under Connected devices.
   - Go to Window -> Device and Simulators
   - Confirm your iPhone appears under connected devices
4) Configure signing
   - In the left sidebar click the project (GuideFollowing)
   - Go to "Signing & Capabilties"
   - Enable "Automatically manage signing"
   - Select your Apple ID under Team (If not listed add your apple account)
5) Select your iPhone as the run destionation
   - Use the device dropdown at the top of Xcode
6) Build and run the app
   - click the Run button or press Cmd + R
7) Trust the developer certificate
   - On your iPhone go to: Settings -> General -> VPN & Device Management -> Developer App -> Trust
8) Launch the app and allow camera access

Running the app after first time setup
- The app will be installed on your phone and can be launched directly from it
- If you make code changes rebuild and run the app again from Xcode
- Once your phone has been paired with your mac you can build wirelessly. Just make sure that both your mac and iPhone are on the same WiFi.

Running both together (iOS Swift App + Backend)
1) Start the backend server:
   - cd GuideFollowingApp/backend/
   - source .venv/bin/activate
   - uvicorn backend:app --reload --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000
2) Make sure your iPhone and computer are on the same WiFi network (Unless connecting via USB)
3) Open the app on your iPhone
4) in the app go to Settings -> Edit IP
5) Enter your computers local IP address

